  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal statutes:\n- The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- The Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- The USA PATRIOT Act\n- The International Money Laundering Abatement and Anti-Terrorism Financing Act\n\n2. Key provisions include:\n- Requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Criminalizing financial transactions intended to conceal illegal proceeds\n- Establishing reporting requirements for cash transactions over $10,000\n- Imposing penalties and criminal sanctions for money laundering activities\n\n3. State-level statutes:\n- Many states have their own money laundering laws that complement federal statutes\n- These often mirror federal regulations and provide additional enforcement mechanisms\n\n4. Penalties can include:\n- Significant fines\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Imprisonment\n- Civil and criminal prosecution\n\n5. Enforcement agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation\n\nThese statutes are designed to detect, prevent, and prosecute financial crimes involving the concealment of illegally obtained money.",
